content.text:
The issue was that `yield()` resumes immediately instead of yielding control to a delayed task that is already ready to run. This happened because `yield()` calls `dispatch()`, which enqueues the continuation of the yielding coroutine to the event loop's queue. The event loop then processes this queue. The delayed tasks were only moved to the main queue *inside* the event loop's processing loop. Since `yield` adds its continuation to the queue *before* the event loop iterates and moves the delayed tasks, the `yield` continuation was executed before the delayed tasks, even if they were overdue.

To fix this, I modified `EventLoopImplBase.enqueue` (which is called by `dispatch`) to check for any ready delayed tasks and move them to the main queue *before* adding the new task. This ensures that if there are overdue delayed tasks, they will be placed in the queue ahead of the task being enqueued (e.g., the `yield` continuation), thus preserving the expected execution order.

I introduced a private helper method `rescheduleDelayedTasks` to share the logic between `enqueue` and `processNextEvent`.

The changes were made in `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/EventLoop.common.kt`.

Verified the fix with a reproduction test case (which passed) and ran existing `EventLoopsTest` (which also passed).

Deleted the temporary test file `kotlinx-coroutines-core/jvm/test/EventLoopYieldTest.kt` before submission.

```kotlin
    private fun rescheduleDelayedTasks() {
        val delayed = _delayed.value
        if (delayed != null && !delayed.isEmpty) {
            val now = nanoTime()
            while (true) {
                // make sure that moving from delayed to queue removes from delayed only after it is added to queue
                // to make sure that 'isEmpty' and `nextTime` that check both of them
                // do not transiently report that both delayed and queue are empty during move
                delayed.removeFirstIf {
                    if (it.timeToExecute(now)) {
                        enqueueImpl(it)
                    } else
                        false
                } ?: break // quit loop when nothing more to remove or enqueueImpl returns false on "isComplete"
            }
        }
    }

    override fun processNextEvent(): Long {
        // unconfined events take priority
        if (processUnconfinedEvent()) return 0
        // queue all delayed tasks that are due to be executed
        rescheduleDelayedTasks()
        // then process one event from queue
        val task = dequeue()
        if (task != null) {
            platformAutoreleasePool { task.run() }
            return 0
        }
        return nextTime
    }

    final override fun dispatch(context: CoroutineContext, block: Runnable) = enqueue(block)

    open fun enqueue(task: Runnable) {
        if (_delayed.value?.let { !it.isEmpty } == true) {
            rescheduleDelayedTasks()
        }
        if (enqueueImpl(task)) {
            // todo: we should unpark only when this delayed task became first in the queue
            unpark()
        } else {
            DefaultExecutor.enqueue(task)
        }
    }
```

